# scheduling.gbnf — MBOX-120 constrained-decoding grammar for `scheduling` drafts.
#
# DESIGN — constrain the BONES, not the prose.
# Same philosophy as reorder.gbnf (see that file's header and the arxiv
# 2603.03305 caveat): enforce only the STRUCTURE a scheduling reply always
# has, and leave every word of the prose decoded FREELY by the model.
#
# Structure enforced (the "bones"):
#   1. a greeting line                  (free text, one line)
#   2. a free-form body                 (one-or-more sentences, NOT constrained)
#   3. a structured proposed-time slot  (a proposed time + a timezone are
#                                         REQUIRED as labelled tokens, but their
#                                         VALUES are free text — the model fills
#                                         them, including bracketed [confirm with
#                                         operator: ...] placeholders)
#   4. a signoff line                   (free text, one line)
#
# What is deliberately NOT constrained: word choice, how many slots the body
# proposes in prose, tone, the literal values after the time/timezone labels.
# The grammar can refuse a reply that omits the proposed-time slot entirely; it
# can NOT force a specific phrasing. Structure is cheap and safe to enforce;
# prose is where constrained decoding hurts, so we leave it alone.
#
# Default OFF behind CONSTRAINED_DECODING_ENABLED (see grammar-dispatch.ts).
# Only the llama.cpp local runtime consumes `grammar`; Ollama ignores it.

root      ::= greeting nl body nl propose nl signoff

greeting  ::= line

# Body: one or more free-text lines. Word choice is entirely up to the model.
body      ::= line (nl line)*

# Proposed-time slot: both labels are required tokens, their values are free.
# The model supplies a concrete time (or a [confirm with operator: ...]
# placeholder) and the timezone it is quoted in.
propose   ::= when-line nl tz-line
when-line ::= ("Proposed" | "Proposed time" | "How about" | "Suggested") ": " value
tz-line   ::= ("Timezone" | "TZ" | "Time zone" | "All times") ": " value

signoff   ::= line

# A line is one or more printable chars (no embedded newline). `value` is the
# same free-text token used after a structured label.
line      ::= char+
value     ::= char+
char      ::= [^\n]
nl        ::= "\n"
